CyclisticUsage

Arvilla

12/20/2021

Task

What we have here is the previous 12 months of Cyclistic usage data. Cyclistic is a bike-share offering composed of a fleet of 5,824 geotracked bicycles with a network of 692 stations across Chicago.

We have been asked to analyze historical bike trip data to identify trends. The main three questions were looking at in order to inform future marketing are: How do annual members and casual riders use the bikes differently? Why would casual riders buy annual memberships? *How can Cyclistic use digital media to influence casual riders to become members?

Today, were looking specifically at the first question.

##Preparing the data

The 12 months of trip data were provided in 12 separate csv files.

all_trips <- rename(all_trips, membership = member_casual)

And drop the columns were not interested in.

all_trips <- select(all_trips, -c(start_lat, start_lng, end_lat, end_lng))

And lets go ahead and add a couple more columns, one for trip duration, one for date, month, and weekday, just for some additional insights.

all_trips$trip_length <- difftime(all_trips$ended_at,all_trips$started_at)
all_trips$date <- as.Date(all_trips$started_at) 
all_trips$month <- format(as.Date(all_trips$date), "%m")
all_trips$day <- format(as.Date(all_trips$date), "%d")
all_trips$day_of_week <- format(as.Date(all_trips$date), "%A")

We convert trip_length to numeric so we can do calculations on it, since time difference can be a bit funny with that.

all_trips$trip_length <- as.numeric(as.character(all_trips$trip_length))
is.numeric(all_trips$trip_length)
## [1] TRUE

We check the trip_length column to make sure its got reasonable values and discover its got 581 negative values and another 493 with 0.

sum(all_trips$trip_length < 0)
## [1] 581
sum(all_trips$trip_length == 0)
## [1] 493
all_trips_2 <- subset(all_trips, trip_length > 0)

We also discover that theres 3912 trips that are over a day long. We save this data to a new tibble to explore more later if desired.

sum(all_trips$trip_length > 86400)
## [1] 3912
day_trips <- subset(all_trips, trip_length > 86400)

But since these and the trips less than 1 second long dont even make up a percentage point of the data, we feel okay removing it and move forward with new data frame.

all_trips_2 <- subset(all_trips, trip_length > 0 & trip_length < 86400)

Now that the data seems to be in pretty good shape, lets see what we can find.

##Analyzing the data

First, well take a look at the trip_length data, both in seconds and in minutes.

summary(all_trips_2$trip_length)

Now that weve got a basic sense of that overall data, lets see how members vs casual users compare.

all_trips_2 %>% 
  group_by(membership) %>% 
  summarize(min = min (trip_length), mean = mean(trip_length)/60, median = median(trip_length)/60, max = max(trip_length)/60)
## # A tibble: 2  5
##   membership   min  mean median   max

## 2 member         1  13.5   9.72 1440.

We find that casual users on average have longer rides.

Lets explore use by weekday. We notice the weekdays are out of order, and fix that.

all_trips_2$day_of_week <- ordered(all_trips_2$day_of_week, levels=c("Sunday", "Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday"))

all_trips_2 %>% 
  group_by(membership, day_of_week) %>% 
  summarize(min = min (trip_length), mean = mean(trip_length), median = median(trip_length), max = max(trip_length), number_of_rides = n())

We find that casual users on average have their longest trips during the weekend by a significant degree and also travel more on the weekends.

Lets go ahead and plot some things out, since visuals tend to be easier to gain insights from.

all_trips_2 %>% 
  group_by(membership, day_of_week) %>% 
  summarize(min = min (trip_length), mean = mean(trip_length), median = median(trip_length), max = max(trip_length), number_of_rides = n()) %>% 
ggplot(aes(x=day_of_week, y=number_of_rides)) + geom_point(mapping=aes(color=membership)) + labs(y="Number of Rides", x="Day of the Week", title="Number of Trips Throughout the Week", color="Type of User") + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'membership'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

ggsave("NumberofTripsThroughoutWeek.png")
## Saving 7 x 5 in image

So we see that casual users definitely use the service differently than members.

Lets also plot out average lengths of trips.

all_trips_2 %>% 
  group_by(membership, day_of_week) %>% 
  summarize(mean_trip = mean(trip_length)/60) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=day_of_week, y=mean_trip)) + geom_point(mapping=aes(color=membership)) + labs(y = "Average Trip in Minutes", x = "Day of Week", color="Type of User", title="Average Trip Length Throughout the Week") + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45))

We can see that casual users also tend to have much longer rides than members.

all_trips_2 %>% 
  group_by(membership, day_of_week, rideable_type) %>% 
  summarize(number_of_rides = n()) %>% 
ggplot(aes(x=day_of_week, y=number_of_rides)) + geom_point(mapping=aes(color=rideable_type)) + facet_wrap(~membership) + labs(x="Day of Week", y="Number of Rides") + scale_y_continuous(labels = function(x) format(x, scientific = FALSE)) + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45)) + scale_color_discrete(name = "Type of Bike", labels = c("Classic", "Docked", "Electric"))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'membership', 'day_of_week'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

all_trips_2 %>% 
    group_by(rideable_type, membership) %>% 
    summarize(number_of_rides = n()) %>% 
    ggplot(aes(x=rideable_type, y=number_of_rides)) + geom_bar(aes(fill = membership), position = "dodge", stat="identity") + labs(x="Type of Bike", y="Number of Rides", title="Number of Rides by Bike Type",fill="Membership") + scale_x_discrete(labels=c("classic_bike" = "Classic", "docked_bike" = "Docked", "electric_bike" = "Electric"))
